In ``JPype1<1.0`` user threads created in Java were being terminated early & abruptly if the main thread completed. Since ``JPype1 >= 1.0`` user threads are now honoured.

This seems like a very welcome improvement :+1:, but I didn't see this in the [changelog](https://jpype.readthedocs.io/en/latest/CHANGELOG.html). Was this intentional, and if so, should it be documented?

Code to emulate (excuse my poor Java):

```
package org.hello_world;


public class hello_world {
    public static void thread_hello() throws Exception {
        System.out.println("Setting up a thread");

        Thread t = new Thread(() -> {
            int count = 0;
            while (count < 10) {
                count++;
                try {
                    Thread.currentThread().sleep(1000);
                } catch (InterruptedException e) {
                }
            }
            System.out.println("Thread finished");
        });
        t.setDaemon(false);
        t.start();

        Thread.sleep(750);
        System.out.println("Done in the main thread");
    }
}
```

Which, after compiling with:

```
javac ./org/hello_world/hello_world.java
jar -c ./org/hello_world/hello_world.java ./org/hello_world/hello_world.class > hello-world.jar
```

And running with:

```
import pathlib

import jpype as jp


HERE = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.absolute()


def test():
    jp.startJVM(f'-Djava.class.path={HERE}/hello-world.jar', convertStrings=False)
    cls = jp.JClass("org.hello_world.hello_world")
    cls.thread_hello()


if __name__ == '__main__':
    test()
```

