I ran into a problem where I implement a Java interface in Python and then add these objects into a HashSet and try to remove such objects from that HashSet: the remove operation calls equal() / __eq__ and this obtains as first argument nicely the Python object, but as second argument an instance of org.jpype.proxy.JPypeInvocationHandler and this object does not permit to access members of the Python object.

Now I am not sure this should work, but it would be very nice for my use case. I use v0.7.1 built from github.

The following is a minimal example that demonstrates the issue, the real code does more useful stuff.

The idea is that the Test1Class constructor gets two sets of objects and subtracts the second from the first. The Test1Interface serves as the interface for the objects and at the same time as provider of the two sets (to keep the example small).

Test1Interface.java
```
package at.ac.tuwien.kr.hexlite.test;

import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.HashSet;

public interface Test1Interface {
   public int hashCode();
   public boolean equals(Object o);
   public String toString();
   public HashSet<ArrayList<Test1Interface> > provide1();
   public HashSet<ArrayList<Test1Interface> > provide2();
};
```

Test1Class.java
```
package at.ac.tuwien.kr.hexlite.test;

import java.util.ArrayList;
import java.util.HashSet;

public class Test1Class {
   public Test1Class(Test1Interface s) {
      HashSet<ArrayList<Test1Interface> > result = new HashSet<ArrayList<Test1Interface> >();
      System.err.println("initial: "+result);
      for(ArrayList<Test1Interface> x : s.provide1()) result.add(x);
      System.err.println("after add: "+result);
      for(ArrayList<Test1Interface> y : s.provide2()) result.remove(y);
      System.err.println("after remove: "+result);
   }
}
```

My Python script:
```
import jpype
jpype.startJVM(convertStrings=False)
from jpype import java
from jpype.types import *

print("Version:"+jpype.__version__)
Test1Interface = JClass("at.ac.tuwien.kr.hexlite.test.Test1Interface")
Test1Class = JClass("at.ac.tuwien.kr.hexlite.test.Test1Class")

@jpype.JImplements(Test1Interface)
class Test1Implementation:
	def __init__(self, something):
		self.something = something

	@jpype.JOverride
	def hashCode(self):
		return int(hash(self.something) & 0x7FFFFFFF)

	@jpype.JOverride
	def provide1(self):
		s = java.util.HashSet()
		
		tup1 = java.util.ArrayList()
		tup1.add(Test1Implementation("foo"))
		s.add(tup1)

		tup2 = java.util.ArrayList()
		tup2.add(Test1Implementation("bar"))
		s.add(tup2)
		return s

	@jpype.JOverride
	def provide2(self):
		s = java.util.HashSet()
		
		tup1 = java.util.ArrayList()
		tup1.add(Test1Implementation("bar"))
		s.add(tup1)

		tup2 = java.util.ArrayList()
		tup2.add(Test1Implementation("baz"))
		s.add(tup2)
		return s

	def __eq__(self, other):
		print("__eq__ repr(self)=%s vs repr(other)=%s", repr(self), repr(other))
		print("__eq__ str(self)=%s vs str(other)=%s", str(self), str(other))

		# does not work, other seems to be a Java-only-usable object - can I cast other to Test1Implementation?
		return self.something == other.something

	@jpype.JOverride
	def equals(self, other):
		return self.__eq__(other)

	def __str__(self):
		return str(self.something)

	@jpype.JOverride
	def toString(self):
		return str(self.something)

i = Test1Implementation("nothing")
c = Test1Class(i)
jpype.shutdownJVM()
```

